## 4. How to run / test

```bash
make check          # full local gate
make backend        # backend only (ruff, black, mypy, bandit, pip-audit, pytest)
make fmt            # auto-format
make dod-check      # doc-consistency guards
```

`make check` (and CI) is the source of truth. Local dev:

```bash
cd backend && python -m venv .venv && . .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt -r requirements-dev.txt
uvicorn {{ python_package }}.main:app --reload
```

---

## 5. Git & branching

- **Branches:** `main` (production) · `develop` (integration) · `feat/*`, `fix/*`, `refactor/*`,
  `docs/*` off `develop`.
- **Never commit directly to `main`.** PRs only; the PR template enforces the ritual.
- **Conventional Commits:** `type(scope): summary` — types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`,
  `test`, `chore`, `security`, `perf`.
- Keep commits focused: one logical change each.

---

## 6. Security workflow

- Run `gitleaks detect` / pre-commit before pushing (hooks do this automatically).
- Any security-relevant change → note it in [`docs/SECURITY.md`](docs/SECURITY.md) and tag the
  commit `security:`.
{% if include_claude_hooks %}- **Local Claude Code hooks** (`.claude/settings.json`) auto-format backend Python and block footguns
  (direct push to `main`, `--no-verify`, dangerous `rm -rf`) and secret writes. These are *ergonomics*
  that shift the guards left — **CI and the branch ruleset are the real, fail-closed enforcement.**
{% endif %}

---

## 7. When in doubt

- **Going long / getting complex?** Stop and split — new file, new module, new ADR.
- **Unsure of a decision?** Write an ADR proposing it rather than deciding silently.
- **Proactively recommend the professional approach** even if not asked.
